crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Silas Cutler (havex [@] chronicle.security), Chronicle Security

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB shared object, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, BuildID[sha1]=666ab12f82022b411c915ded855d53448e21847f, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is an LD_PRELOAD rootkit that hides files, processes, and network connections. It hooks standard C library functions (`readdir`, `fopen`, `open`, `stat`, etc.) to filter out information related to its components. It identifies its own processes by checking for the paths `/lib/libxselinux` or `/usr/lib/libxselinux` in their command lines. To hide network connections, it intercepts reads from files like `/proc/net/tcp`, finds its own socket inodes, and filters them from the output returned to the user application (e.g., `netstat`). The malware uses single-byte XOR with key 0xFE to obfuscate internal strings.
